'''Ōnishi Yoritake''' (大西 頼武, ? - {{ill|Tenshō|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō (Momoyama period)|qq=}} 5 ({{ill|1577|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1577|qq=}})) was a {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}} {{ill|local lord|ja|国人領主|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/local lord|qq=}} of {{ill|Awa Province (Tokushima)|ja|阿波国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Awa Province (Tokushima)|qq=}}. He was the lord of {{ill|Hakuchi Castle|ja|白地城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakuchi Castle|qq=}} and held the title Izumo-no-kami. His brothers included Mototake, and his children were {{ill|Ōnishi Kakuyō|ja|大西覚養|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōnishi Kakuyō|qq=}}, Yoriharu, and {{ill|Ōnishi Yoritomo|ja|大西頼包|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōnishi Yoritomo|qq=}}.

== Life ==
The {{ill|Ōnishi clan|ja|大西氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōnishi clan|qq=}} originated during the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}}, when the {{ill|Kondō clan|ja|近藤氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kondō clan|qq=}}, sent as estate stewards from the central government, settled in the Ōnishi region and adopted the Ōnishi name.

Yoritake initially served the {{ill|Hosokawa clan|ja|細川氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hosokawa clan|qq=}} but later strengthened his influence by marrying the sister of {{ill|Miyoshi Nagayoshi|ja|三好長慶|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyoshi Nagayoshi|qq=}}. This alliance enabled the Ōnishi clan to dominate western Awa, southern {{ill|Sanuki Province|ja|讃岐国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanuki Province|qq=}}, eastern {{ill|Iyo Province|ja|伊予国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iyo Province|qq=}}, and northern {{ill|Tosa Province|ja|土佐国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tosa Province|qq=}}.

As {{ill|Chōsokabe Motochika|ja|長宗我部元親|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōsokabe Motochika|qq=}} began his campaign to unify {{ill|Shikoku|ja|四国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikoku|qq=}}, the strategically located Hakuchi Castle became a primary target. By this time, Yoritake had reportedly passed leadership of the clan to his son, Kakuyō.

In {{ill|Tenshō|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō (Momoyama period)|qq=}} 5 (1577), Motochika launched his invasion of Awa. The current head, Kakuyō, initially sought peace by offering his brother, Yoritomo, as a hostage. However, he soon defected to the {{ill|Miyoshi clan|ja|三好氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyoshi clan|qq=}} at their request.

Motochika responded by capturing {{ill|Tao Castle|ja|田尾城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tao Castle|qq=}}, a key fortification of Hakuchi Castle, within just two days, guided by the hostage Yoritomo. While Kakuyō fled to Sanuki, Yoritake is said to have committed seppuku during the conflict.
